# Vocab:

| Term / Acronym | Definition |
| :---- | :---- |
| **AC (Alternating Current) Power** | Electricity where the flow of electric charge periodically reverses direction, creating a sinusoidal wave. Transformers can "step up" (increase) AC voltage for long-distance travel, reducing energy loss, and then "step down" (decrease) the voltage for safe use in homes. |
| **Power Transformer** | Changes AC voltage levels for power transmission and distribution. Step-up transformers raise voltage for efficient long-distance travel; step-down transformers reduce it for end-use. |
| **PD (Partial Discharge)** | Small, repeated electrical sparking inside insulation that slowly destroys it without immediately causing a short circuit. |
| **PD Waveforms** | Electrical signals showing tiny breakdowns in insulation, vital for diagnosing equipment health. PD activity clusters at specific voltage phases (positive or negative). |
| **Internal Discharge** | Tiny electrical sparking occurring within voids or cavities inside solid or liquid insulation material. |
| **Corona Discharge** | A faint electrical discharge caused by ionization of gas around a high-voltage conductor, typically at sharp points or edges. |
| **Surface Discharge** | Partial discharge that travels along insulation surfaces, often forming conductive tracks that lead to failure. |
| **Noise Patterns** | Unwanted signals in PD measurements that come from external sources rather than actual insulation discharge. |
| **EM (Electromagnetic) Sensor Data** | Data captured by sensors that detect electromagnetic signals emitted during partial discharge events. |
| **HFCT (High-Frequency Current Transformer)** | A sensor clamped around a cable or ground wire that detects high-frequency current pulses produced by PD. |
| **Coupling Capacitor** | A device used to detect PD signals by capacitively coupling to the high-voltage conductor and filtering out the PD-frequency signals. |
| **TEV (Transient Earth Voltage)** | A short-lived voltage pulse appearing on the external surface of metal-clad switchgear during a PD event. |
| **ADC (Analog-to-Digital Converter)** | Hardware that converts continuous analog signals (like EM waveforms) into discrete digital values for software processing. |
| **Noise Floor** | The inherent background "static" in a system; signals below this level cannot be reliably distinguished from noise. |
| **Noise Floor Analysis** | Measuring the inherent background noise in a system to determine the lowest detectable signal level. |
| **Noise-to-Signal Ratio** | The ratio of unwanted background noise to the actual signal of interest. (The inverse of SNR). |
| **Wavelet Energy** | A signal analysis technique that decomposes a waveform into frequency components at different scales to characterize the signal type. |
| **Histogram Knee** | A method for setting thresholds by finding the "knee" point (where a curve bends sharply) to separate signal from noise. |
| **Trigger Threshold** | A predefined signal level that, when exceeded, tells the system to start recording a waveform. |
| **Pulse Width** | The duration a signal stays at its high (active) level, measured from the start of the leading edge to the end of the trailing edge. |
| **Phase Angle** | The position within the AC power cycle (0°–360°) where a discharge event occurs; used to identify failure modes. |
| **Rise Time / Fall Time** | How quickly a PD pulse's voltage increases to its peak and decreases back down. |
| **Waveform Clustering** | Grouping PD waveforms by shape similarity to identify distinct discharge types before classification. |
| **Multimodal Data Fusion** | Combining data from multiple sensor types (e.g., EM, acoustic, chemical) to improve diagnostic accuracy. |
| **Middleware** | Software that sits between raw sensor data and the ML pipeline, handling format conversion and preprocessing. |
| **Precision** | A metric measuring accuracy: of all positive predictions, how many were actually correct? (Penalizes False Positives). |
| **Recall** | A metric measuring coverage: of all actual cases, how many did the model find? (Penalizes False Negatives). |
| **F1 Score** | The harmonic mean of Precision and Recall, providing a single score that balances both metrics. |

Meanings of HFCT, ADC, MSPS, and coupling capacitor in the context of electrical power grids (monitoring, protection, and sensing): HFCT (High-Frequency Current Transformer) A current sensor designed to measure high-frequency components of current (typically kHz–MHz range), not the 50/60 Hz fundamental. In grid applications Partial discharge (PD) detection in cables, transformers, switchgear High-frequency transient monitoring EMI and fault diagnostics Key point: HFCTs detect fast current pulses that conventional CTs cannot. ADC (Analog-to-Digital Converter) An electronic component that converts an analog voltage or current signal into digital samples. In grid applications Digitizing signals from HFCTs, voltage dividers, Rogowski coils Feeding digital protection relays, PD analyzers, and monitoring systems Key parameters Resolution (bits) Sampling rate (MSPS) Input bandwidth Noise performance MSPS (Mega Samples Per Second) A unit of sampling rate for an ADC. Meaning 1 MSPS \= 1,000,000 samples per second In grid applications High MSPS (10–500+ MSPS): transient detection, PD monitoring, switching events Low MSPS (kSPS): power quality, RMS, harmonics Rule of thumb ADC sampling rate should be at least 5–10× the highest frequency of interest for accurate transient capture. Coupling Capacitor A capacitor used to pass high-frequency signals while blocking DC and low-frequency power components. In grid applications Couples high-frequency PD or transient signals from high-voltage equipment to measurement electronics Blocks dangerous mains or HV DC/AC from reaching sensors and ADCs Typical uses PD measurement on HV cables and GIS Transient voltage sensing Signal isolation and protection Key idea: It safely extracts information without transferring power. How they work together (typical PD monitoring chain) HFCT senses high-frequency current pulses on a cable or ground lead Coupling capacitor filters and isolates the signal ADC digitizes the conditioned signal MSPS rating determines how well fast events are captured![][image2]
